#----------------[  DAY 2 ]---------------#



'awk' command is functionally very similar to the 'cut' command.
Awk is mostly used for pattern scanning and processing. It searches one or more files to see if they contain lines that matches with the specified patterns,
and then perform the associated actions. Awk is abbreviated from the names of the developers â€“ Aho, Weinberger, and Kernighan.




awk -F      >> indicates field seperator (like -d for delimiter in 'cut')


awk -F:   >>    would field seperate on :


*** awk by default, with no options uses ' ' or space as its field seperator ***


Example syntax:
        awk -F: '{print $1}'         displays 1st field delimited by a ":"
        awk '{print $2}'             displays 2nd field, delimited automatically by space
        awk '{print $0}'             displays all string data that matches
		

        
Terminal Examples:

	>>>	cat /etc/passwd
	
		root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
		daemon:x:1:1:daemon:/usr/sbin:/usr/sbin/nologin
		bin:x:2:2:bin:/bin:/usr/sbin/nologin
		sys:x:3:3:sys:/dev:/usr/sbin/nologin
		sync:x:4:65534:sync:/bin:/bin/sync
	
	>>>	cat /etc/passwd | head -n5 | awk -F: '{print "User="$1,"UID="$3,"GID="$4}'
	
		User=root UID=0 GID=0
		User=daemon UID=1 GID=1
		User=bin UID=2 GID=2
		User=sys UID=3 GID=3
		User=sync UID=4 GID=65534
===========================================================================================================================================================		
		
sort command:


		sort -t		>>		the -t specifies delimiter

		sort -t		>>		would delimit on colons

		sort -t: -k3 -n		>>		-k3 specifies that it is sorting on field 3, -t 
		
		
===========================================================================================================================================================	
		
uniq command:



brother command of sort. often used in conjunction with it


